---
import Section from "~/components/Section.astro";
import Stage from "~/components/Stage.astro";

// Toy example: N = 8, T = 4, M = 4. 2N = 16 cells in the hint row.
// 8 real indices (0..7) randomly permuted among the 16 cells, the other
// 8 cells are ⊥. Segments are partial — this matches the paper's own
// Figure 1 (page 3), which shows a segment of the form [2, ⊥, ⊥, 1].
const cells: (number | null)[] = [
  3, 6, null, null,   // Segment 0  — contains the query target (q = 6 at cell 1)
  7, null, 4, null,   // Segment 1
  null, 5, 0, null,   // Segment 2  — replacement will come from here (cell 10)
  null, 1, null, 2,   // Segment 3
];
const cellW = 36;
const cellH = 30;
const gap = 2;
const rowX = 20;
const rowY = 50;
const T = 4;

// Query example: q = 6 is at cell 1 (segment 0, position r = 1 within the segment).
// Segment 0 contents are [3, 6, ⊥, ⊥]. The client builds Q by reading segment 0
// top-to-bottom and swapping position r with Access(cell 10) = 0.
// Q ends up = [3, 0, ⊥, ⊥]: Q[0]=3 (original), Q[1]=0 (swap), Q[2]=⊥, Q[3]=⊥.
// Cell 10 sits at position 2 of segment 2 — a different within-segment position
// than r, matching the paper's Algorithm 3 line 8 (sample uniformly; no
// positional constraint).
const queryValue = 6;
const queryCell = 1;
const swapCell = 10;
const requestValues: (number | null)[] = [3, 0, null, null];
---

<Section id="harmonypir-hint-row" num="06" title="HarmonyPIR — the hint row">
  <p>
    The client's local state after the offline phase is one long row of
    <code>2N</code> cells, called the <strong>hint row</strong>. Half the
    cells hold real database indices, permuted randomly; the other half are
    empty (written <code>⊥</code>). The permutation is private to the client
    — the server never learns which cell holds which index.
  </p>
  <p>
    The row is then split into <code>M = 2N/T</code> contiguous
    <strong>segments</strong> of <code>T</code> cells each. For every
    segment, the client stores one small value, the <strong>hint parity</strong>:
    the XOR of the database entries at the real indices in that segment.
    That's it — <code>M</code> hint parities total, each the size of one
    database row. For a balanced choice <code>T ≈ √(2N)</code> the hint
    store comes out to √<code>N</code> rows' worth of data.
  </p>

  <Stage
    caption="Toy example: N=8, T=4. The client's hint row has 16 cells; 8 hold real indices 0..7, permuted; 8 are empty. One hint parity per segment."
    label="Hint row + hint parities"
  >
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 260" role="img"
      aria-label="Sixteen cells split into four segments; each segment's real indices XOR into a single hint parity below.">

      <text x="20" y="24" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        Hint row — 2N = 16 cells, grouped into M = 4 segments of T = 4
      </text>

      {cells.map((v, i) => {
        const x = rowX + i * (cellW + gap);
        const isReal = v !== null;
        return (
          <g>
            <rect x={x} y={rowY} width={cellW} height={cellH} rx="3"
              fill={isReal ? "var(--accent-bg)" : "var(--bg-elev-2)"}
              stroke={isReal ? "var(--accent)" : "var(--border)"}/>
            <text x={x + cellW / 2} y={rowY + cellH / 2 + 4}
              text-anchor="middle" font-size="11"
              font-family="ui-monospace, monospace"
              fill={isReal ? "var(--accent)" : "var(--fg-dim)"}
              font-weight="600">
              {isReal ? v : "⊥"}
            </text>
          </g>
        );
      })}

      <!-- Segment dividers (between T-sized chunks) -->
      {[1, 2, 3].map((k) => {
        const x = rowX + k * T * (cellW + gap) - gap / 2;
        return (
          <line x1={x} y1={rowY - 4} x2={x} y2={rowY + cellH + 20}
            stroke="var(--fg-muted)" stroke-width="1"/>
        );
      })}

      <!-- Segment labels -->
      {[0, 1, 2, 3].map((s) => {
        const x = rowX + s * T * (cellW + gap) + (T * (cellW + gap)) / 2 - gap / 2;
        return (
          <text x={x} y={rowY + cellH + 15} text-anchor="middle"
            class="svg-label" font-size="10">Seg {s}</text>
        );
      })}

      <!-- Hint parities stacked below — one line per segment, full-width boxes
           so the XOR of four indices isn't cramped. -->
      <text x="20" y="122" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        Hint parities (stored locally by the client)
      </text>
      {[
        { s: 0, text: "H[0]  =  DB[3] ⊕ DB[6]", note: "from segment 0" },
        { s: 1, text: "H[1]  =  DB[7] ⊕ DB[4]", note: "from segment 1" },
        { s: 2, text: "H[2]  =  DB[5] ⊕ DB[0]", note: "from segment 2" },
        { s: 3, text: "H[3]  =  DB[1] ⊕ DB[2]", note: "from segment 3" },
      ].map(({ text, note }, i) => {
        const y = 134 + i * 22;
        return (
          <g>
            <rect x="20" y={y} width="640" height="18" rx="3"
              fill="var(--bg-elev-2)" stroke="var(--border)"/>
            <text x="32" y={y + 13} font-size="10.5"
              font-family="ui-monospace, monospace" fill="var(--fg-muted)">
              {text}
            </text>
            <text x="648" y={y + 13} text-anchor="end" font-size="9"
              class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-dim)" font-style="italic">
              {note}
            </text>
          </g>
        );
      })}

      <text x="20" y="244" font-size="10" class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-muted)" font-style="italic">
        For N ≈ 2²⁰ with T ≈ √(2N) ≈ 1448: the client keeps ~1448 hint
        parities, each one row wide — √N storage total.
      </text>
    </svg>
  </Stage>

  <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">One online query, from start to finish</h3>
  <p>
    Say the client wants database row <code>q = 6</code>. It looks up where
    the value <code>6</code> lives in its hint row: segment <code>s = 0</code>,
    position <code>r = 1</code>. Segment <code>0</code>'s contents are
    <code>[3, 6, ⊥, ⊥]</code> — only two of its four cells hold real
    indices, the other two are empty. The client builds the request
    <code>Q</code> by copying segment <code>0</code>'s contents straight
    through, <em>except</em> it replaces slot <code>r</code> with the
    value at a uniformly sampled cell outside segment <code>0</code> —
    say cell <code>10</code>, which holds <code>0</code>. (The algorithm
    picks that cell uniformly from the whole hint row outside segment
    <code>s</code>; there's no constraint on its within-segment position.)
  </p>
  <p>
    The resulting request <code>Q = [3, 0, ⊥, ⊥]</code> goes to the server
    as plain database indices, with <code>⊥</code> marking slots the
    server should skip. The server looks up the non-empty entries and
    returns <code>R[0] = DB[3]</code> and <code>R[1] = DB[0]</code>;
    positions <code>2</code> and <code>3</code> have no response. The
    client XORs its stored parity against every returned value at a
    position other than <code>r</code>:
  </p>
  <pre><code>answer = H[0] ⊕ R[0]
       = (DB[3] ⊕ DB[6]) ⊕ DB[3]
       = DB[6]</code></pre>
  <p>
    <code>R[1]</code> is skipped because that was the swap position — its
    value, <code>DB[0]</code>, has nothing to do with <code>q</code>.
    <code>R[2]</code> and <code>R[3]</code> simply don't exist; if you
    prefer to write them, treat them as <code>0</code>, which leaves the
    XOR unchanged. In a <em>full</em> segment of four real values, the
    answer line would have four terms instead of one — the same formula,
    just more non-⊥ slots to XOR.
  </p>

  <Stage
    caption="Request Q is a length-T batch built from segment s, with position r swapped to a freshly sampled random cell. The client already holds H[s]; the server's response completes the XOR that isolates DB[q]."
    label="One query: Q, R, and the XOR that recovers DB[q]"
  >
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 300" role="img"
      aria-label="Walkthrough: locate q in the hint row, build request Q of T indices with one slot swapped, receive response R, XOR with H[s] to get DB[q]."
      data-anim="harmony-query">

      <defs>
        <marker id="hq-arr" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5"
          markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto">
          <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="var(--fg-muted)"/>
        </marker>
      </defs>

      <!-- Hint row (condensed) -->
      <text x="20" y="18" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        1. Locate q = 6 → cell 1 (segment 0, position 1)
      </text>
      {cells.map((v, i) => {
        const smallW = 32;
        const smallGap = 2;
        const x = 20 + i * (smallW + smallGap);
        const y = 28;
        const isReal = v !== null;
        const isQuery = i === queryCell;
        const isSwap = i === swapCell;
        return (
          <g class={isQuery ? "step step-q" : (isSwap ? "step step-swap" : "")}>
            <rect x={x} y={y} width={smallW} height={26} rx="3"
              fill={isQuery ? "var(--ok)"
                : isSwap ? "#e8a33c"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent-bg)"
                : "var(--bg-elev-2)"}
              stroke={isQuery ? "var(--ok)"
                : isSwap ? "#c98728"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent)"
                : "var(--border)"}
              stroke-width={isQuery || isSwap ? "1.5" : "1"}/>
            <text x={x + smallW / 2} y={y + 17}
              text-anchor="middle" font-size="10"
              font-family="ui-monospace, monospace"
              fill={isQuery ? "#0a0b0f"
                : isSwap ? "#0a0b0f"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent)"
                : "var(--fg-dim)"}
              font-weight={isQuery || isSwap ? "700" : "500"}>
              {isReal ? v : "⊥"}
            </text>
          </g>
        );
      })}
      {/* Segment dividers on the small row */}
      {[1, 2, 3].map((k) => {
        const x = 20 + k * T * 34 - 1;
        return (
          <line x1={x} y1={24} x2={x} y2={58}
            stroke="var(--fg-muted)" stroke-width="1"/>
        );
      })}

      <!-- Request Q -->
      <text x="20" y="90" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        2. Build request Q — copy segment 0's contents, swap position r = 1 with cell 10's value
      </text>
      {requestValues.map((v, i) => {
        const x = 20 + i * 60;
        const y = 100;
        const isSwap = i === 1;
        const isEmpty = v === null;
        return (
          <g class="step step-req">
            <rect x={x} y={y} width={54} height={30} rx="4"
              fill={isEmpty ? "var(--bg-elev-2)"
                : isSwap ? "#e8a33c"
                : "var(--accent)"}
              opacity={isEmpty ? "1" : isSwap ? "0.85" : "0.75"}
              stroke={isEmpty ? "var(--border)"
                : isSwap ? "#c98728"
                : "var(--accent)"}/>
            <text x={x + 27} y={y + 19}
              text-anchor="middle" font-size="11"
              font-family="ui-monospace, monospace"
              fill={isEmpty ? "var(--fg-dim)" : "#0a0b0f"}
              font-weight="700">
              Q[{i}]={isEmpty ? "⊥" : v}
            </text>
          </g>
        );
      })}
      <text x="80" y="148" font-size="9" class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-muted)" font-style="italic">
        sampled from cell 10
      </text>
      <text x="440" y="148" font-size="9" class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-muted)" font-style="italic" text-anchor="middle">
        ⊥ slots come from the empty cells of segment 0 — server skips them
      </text>

      <!-- Server + response -->
      <text x="20" y="178" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        3. Server looks up each non-⊥ slot and returns those rows
      </text>
      <g class="step step-resp">
        <rect x="20" y="188" width="640" height="34" rx="5"
          fill="var(--bg-elev-2)" stroke="var(--border)"/>
        <text x="340" y="209" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11"
          font-family="ui-monospace, monospace" fill="var(--fg)">
          R[0] = DB[3],   R[1] = DB[0]          (R[2], R[3] absent — Q had ⊥ there)
        </text>
      </g>

      <!-- XOR -->
      <text x="20" y="246" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        4. XOR H[0] with every returned R[i] at a position other than r = 1
      </text>
      <g class="step step-answer">
        <rect x="20" y="256" width="640" height="30" rx="5"
          fill="var(--ok)" opacity="0.18" stroke="var(--ok)"/>
        <text x="340" y="276" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11"
          font-family="ui-monospace, monospace" fill="var(--ok)" font-weight="700">
          H[0] ⊕ R[0]  =  (DB[3] ⊕ DB[6]) ⊕ DB[3]  =  DB[6]   ✓
        </text>
      </g>
    </svg>
  </Stage>

  <p>
    Two things are worth pausing on. First, privacy: the server sees a
    length-<code>T</code> batch of plain database indices (some of them
    <code>⊥</code>). Because the hint row is a uniformly random
    permutation hidden from the server — and because slot <code>r</code>
    was replaced by the value at an independently sampled random cell —
    the distribution of that batch is indistinguishable from a uniform
    sample of <code>T</code> cells from the whole hint row. The batch
    contains <code>q</code>, but the server can't point to which slot it
    is, and can't even rule out slots whose values came from segment
    <code>s</code>'s other cells. Second, efficiency: the request has at
    most <code>T</code> indices, the response at most <code>T</code> rows,
    and the client's online work is a handful of XORs plus one hint
    lookup. With <code>T ≈ √(2N)</code> that's √<code>N</code> work
    online, against a total database of <code>N</code> rows.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>An implementation detail.</strong> On the wire, HarmonyPIR
    does not actually transmit the <code>⊥</code> markers shown above.
    Sending only the non-empty slots would let the server count how
    many cells in segment <code>s</code> are still occupied — a count
    that drifts upward as the client consumes hints, leaking both
    query progress and which slot is the real query each round. The
    fix replaces every <code>⊥</code> with a freshly sampled random
    index and XOR-cancels the dummies client-side; the
    <em>Hiding the empty count</em> page walks through it.
  </p>
  <p>
    We've also glossed over one bigger thing: after the query runs,
    the hint row has to change — otherwise a second query into the
    same segment would leak. The next page handles that, and the
    crypto choice that makes the whole scheme run fast enough to
    matter.
  </p>
</Section>

<style>
  [data-anim="harmony-query"] .step { opacity: 0; }

  [data-anim="harmony-query"].play .step-q {
    animation: hq-in 0.5s var(--ease) 0.2s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="harmony-query"].play .step-swap {
    animation: hq-in 0.5s var(--ease) 1.0s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="harmony-query"].play .step-req {
    animation: hq-in 0.5s var(--ease) 1.6s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="harmony-query"].play .step-resp {
    animation: hq-in 0.5s var(--ease) 2.4s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="harmony-query"].play .step-answer {
    animation: hq-in 0.5s var(--ease) 3.0s forwards;
  }

  @keyframes hq-in { to { opacity: 1; } }

  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    [data-anim="harmony-query"] .step { opacity: 1 !important; }
  }
</style>

<script is:inline>
  document.querySelectorAll('[data-anim="harmony-query"]').forEach((svg) => {
    const stage = svg.closest("[data-stage]");
    const run = () => {
      svg.classList.remove("play");
      void svg.getBoundingClientRect();
      svg.classList.add("play");
    };
    stage?.addEventListener("stage:visible", run);
    svg.addEventListener("click", run);
  });
</script>
